## Common Mistakes

- Providing vague or incomplete context - When you ask Claude Code to make changes without explaining the surrounding code, dependencies, or requirements, the agent may produce solutions that don't integrate properly with your codebase
- Ignoring context window limitations - Not considering that large codebases exceed context limits can lead to Claude Code making changes without awareness of relevant code, resulting in inconsistent or conflicting modifications
- Treating Claude Code as a single-turn tool - Starting fresh with each request instead of leveraging conversation history means losing accumulated context about your project conventions and preferences
- Over-specifying execution details - Micromanaging the exact steps instead of letting Claude Code plan its approach can actually reduce the quality of the solution by constraining the agent's problem-solving capabilities
- Not verifying after execution - Assuming changes are correct without checking the actual output can lead to subtle bugs or unintended modifications propagating through your codebase
- Creating conflicting multi-agent tasks without coordination - When using multiple agents, failing to define clear boundaries and interfaces can result in duplicated effort or integration conflicts
- Providing outdated context - Referencing old file states or cancelled changes in your requests can lead to Claude Code making decisions based on incorrect assumptions


## Best Practices

- Structure your requests to follow the agent loop naturally - Begin with clear problem descriptions, include relevant code context, specify constraints, and explicitly state verification criteria to help Claude Code navigate through explore, plan, execute, and verify phases more effectively
- Manage context strategically by focusing on the most relevant files and information - When working on large projects, explicitly identify which files are most relevant to the current task and provide clear boundaries around the scope of work
- Build conversation context progressively - Start with exploration and planning phases where you establish understanding before requesting major changes, allowing Claude Code to accumulate knowledge about your project
- Use explicit verification requests - After Claude Code completes changes, ask it to verify the modifications by running tests, checking the file contents, or confirming the changes match the requirements
- When working with multiple agents, define clear interfaces and responsibilities - Ensure each agent understands its scope, what it should not modify, and how it should communicate with other agents about shared components
- Maintain awareness of context window usage - Periodically summarize or refocus the conversation to ensure Claude Code has accurate and relevant context for ongoing work
- Provide feedback when Claude Code makes incorrect assumptions - Explicitly correct misunderstandings and explain why certain approaches won't work, helping the agent learn and adjust its approach in real-time

